    {
      "id": "ac1238d6d1a7132f55da912f851c336e425c278c",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 12,
        "name": "wangdi",
        "email": "di.wang@intel.com",
        "username": "wangdi",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2015-01-17 07:27:28.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 6:\n\n\"I don't think the changes to ll_dir_ioctl() are correct. This code is way to shaggy. Giving a -1 at least until I can sort it out.\"\n\nDo you still concern about IOC_MDC_GETFILEINFO on striped directory? I already add check in ll_dir_ioctl. \n\nTBH  I think it is more about technical debt on utils. i.e. it is probably not good to retrieve the FILEINFO by (parent, name), instead they should all call ioctl by inode. \nSo how about you create a new ticket to fix utils. And let me land this patch, because this patch also fix some problem for merge attr, and also \nhttp://review.whamcloud.com/13432 is based on this patch, which will fix racer problem.  I really hope they can all be landed to 2.7. Thanks!",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 6
    },
    {
      "id": "26d2bcac4f50b4022c0995e536c5038ca516f03c",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2015-01-17 08:14:36.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 6:\n\nThere is a specific reason to do ioctl(GETFILEINFO) using { parent, name } instead of ioctl() on each file separately - to avoid opening, locking, and closing each file on the client if that is not needed. The GETFILEINFO ioctl can be done on the patent dir with a single open for all files in that directory, and it also doesn't pollute the client dcache with millions of dentries when traversing a large filesystem.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 6
    },
    {
      "id": "95b760a5f6e7df8accfb0b04229193617f8c64d5",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2015-01-17 08:15:44.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 6:\n\nPS: feel free to add a comment to that effect to lfs or ll_file_ioctl() so it is available the next time someone wonders.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 6
    },
    {
      "id": "e30a9b1785a36896b640c993b89180143855d952",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 12,
        "name": "wangdi",
        "email": "di.wang@intel.com",
        "username": "wangdi",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2015-01-17 20:32:27.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 6:\n\nSo it seems we can confine this FILEINFO ioctl to regular file only. i.e. once the client find out this is being called for a directory, let's return EINVAL. Unluckily this is what lfs does now. \n\nThe main reason here is that without inode cache, it is not easy to operate on striped dir (merge attr etc). And I do not see why do we want to build the inode cache.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 6
    },
