    {
      "id": "49a1c71f961c9ffdce9e14c4e7c103a56991f080",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 101,
        "name": "Lai Siyao",
        "email": "lai.siyao@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "laisiyao"
      },
      "date": "2015-01-19 01:45:45.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 7: Code-Review+1\n\n(2 comments)",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 7
    },
    {
      "id": "543dede382754c73438d78d8ae919ff4220edb7b",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 177,
        "name": "John Hammond",
        "email": "jhammond@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "jhammond"
      },
      "date": "2015-01-19 18:50:57.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 7: Code-Review-1\n\n(3 comments)\n\nI see that there are several issues other than LU-5937 that are addressed by this patch. I'm sorry to hold up their fixes but they should have been put in a different change. While this seems to be correct, it's the wrong fix. For a regular file we do not assume that these ioctls return fully valid attributes. Instead if the size (or other attribute) is really needed then we call IOC_LOV_GETINFO later on. I suggest that directories be handled in the same way but by calling fstat() instead of an ioctl.\n\nIn this case we also do not need to exclude the use of IOC_MDC_GETFILEINFO for directories. Which is good because we are also using this ioctl when we have dentries with d_type == DT_UNKNOWN.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 7
    },
    {
      "id": "cbaa8476891be11ea18bfc24c297785d0fa422dc",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 12,
        "name": "wangdi",
        "email": "di.wang@intel.com",
        "username": "wangdi",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2015-01-19 20:45:15.000000000",
      "message": "Abandoned\n\nabandon this change. John will fix this in http://review.whamcloud.com/13456",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 7
    }
  ],
